Million-aire: How census tracts affect air quality monitoring in Ventura County

Kayla Geronimo-Anctil

This page uses the following packages:

  • sf
  • tidyverse
  • RAQSAPI
  • flextable
  • shadowtext
  • ggdark

Research Hypotheses:

  • Team Research Hypotheses: Marginalized communities are subjected to higher than average levels of PM2.5 and ozone.
  • Kaylas Research Hypothesis: The biggest gaps in county air data are in DACs.
  • Ashleys Research Hypothesis: Childhood asthma correlates with VC air quality. PM2.5 shows the clearest trend.

PurpleAir

To get purpleair.csv, the terminal/Bash was used to retrieve monitor data from PurpleAir. The only monitor data that I could retrieve was public, so if any monitors were private I couldnt use them in the analysis.
The EPSG code for NAD83 / California Zone 5 (in meters) is 26945. To transform an sf object into this CRS, you will see this piece of code again later: ... %>% st_transform(26945).

pa_monitors <- read_csv("purpleair.csv")

#By convention, the coordinate reference system used for longitude / latitude data is WGS 1984, represented with the EPSG code 4326
#Had to go in terms of convention because the dataset does not say what crs is used, and I couldn't find this online
pa_monitors_sf <- pa_monitors %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude","latitude"), #turn pa_monitors into an sf object
               crs = 4326) %>% 
  st_transform(26945) #26945 is the epsg code for nad83 / california zone 5 in meters

CalEnviroScreen4.0 (CES4)

These were downloaded off of the CES website.

CES4_main <- read_csv("data_raw/CES4_spreadsheet.xlsx - CES4.0FINAL_results.csv")
CES4_demo <- read_csv("data_raw/CES4_spreadsheet.xlsx - Copy of Demographic Profile.csv")

CES4_join <- full_join(CES4_main, CES4_demo, by = c("Census Tract", "CES 4.0 Score", "CES 4.0 Percentile", "CES 4.0 Percentile Range", 
                                              "Total Population", "California County"))

CES4 <- CES4_join %>% 
  filter(`California County` == "Ventura")

Before running anything that uses the RAQSAPI (R AQS API) package, you need to run your credentials. As I do not want to share my API key publicly, here is the method that I used:

#think of aqs credentials like how often you call in the library (once every time that you start a new R session)
aqs_credentials(username = "YOUR_USERNAME", 
                         key = "YOUR_API_KEY")

California FIPS = 06
County code:

  • Ventura = 111
  • Santa Barbara = 083
  • Los Angeles = 037

Parameters by class:

  • Ozone = 44201,
  • PM2.5 - Local Conditions = 88101

Ventura County

This chunk below is just finding the monitors that were operating in 2020, that were collecting Ozone and PM2.5 data. This is for Ventura County.

aqs_monitorsK <- aqs_monitors_by_county(
  parameter = c("44201", "88101"),
  bdate=as.Date("20200101", format="%Y%m%d"),
  edate=as.Date("20201231", format="%Y%m%d"),
  stateFIPS = "06",
  countycode = "111")

Here is what that looks like

aqs_monitorsK

And now I am just turning it into an sf object. See the first code chunk under PurpleAir for more.

# datum column lists it as NAD83, EPSG code 4269
aqs_monitorsK_sf <- aqs_monitorsK %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude","latitude"), 
               crs = 4269) %>% 
  st_transform(26945)

Santa Barbara County

I have to do the same as above but for Santa Barbara County, in case that a VC census tract is closer to an SB AQS monitor than to a VC one.

#Have to do santa barbara because maybe a census tract is closer to a santa barbara aqs monitor than to a vc one
aqs_monitorsSB <- RAQSAPI::aqs_monitors_by_county(
  parameter = c("44201", "88101"),
  bdate=as.Date("20190101", format="%Y%m%d"),
  edate=as.Date("20191231", format="%Y%m%d"),
  stateFIPS = "06",
  countycode = "083")


aqs_monitorsSB_sf1 <-   aqs_monitorsSB %>% 
  filter(datum == "WGS84") %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude","latitude"), 
           crs = 4326) %>% 
  st_transform(26945) 
    
aqs_monitorsSB_sf2 <- aqs_monitorsSB %>% 
  filter(datum == "NAD83") %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("longitude","latitude"), 
           crs = 4269) %>% 
  st_transform(26945) 

aqs_monitorsSB_sf <- rbind(aqs_monitorsSB_sf1, aqs_monitorsSB_sf2)

tigris

From Analyzing US Census Data: Methods, Maps, and Models in R tigris is a useful package for getting TIGER/Line shapefiles into your R geospatial projects without having to navigate the Census website.

#cb=TRUE is cartographic boundary instead of TIGER/Line boundary (looks like it gave boundaries into the water)
vc_tracts <- tigris::tracts("CA", "Ventura", year = "2019", cb=TRUE) %>% 
  filter(!(TRACTCE=="980000")) %>%  #filtered out one of the islands down below
  filter(!(TRACTCE == "990100")) %>% 
  st_transform(26945)

stjoin_filter <- function(y,a,indicator){
 #called it y, a instead of x,y, because of below function... I know it might be confusing but im sorry im on time crunch
   st_join(y,a) %>% 
    filter({{indicator}} >= 75)
}
CES4_delete_sf <- stjoin_filter(vc_tracts_pop, CES4_sf, `Solid Waste Pctl`)

Statistical Tests

monitor_ttest <- function(x, y, a, indicator) {
  z <- stjoin_filter(y, a, {{indicator}})
  # find points within GEOIDs
  monitors_in_tract <- st_join(x,y, join=st_within)
  # count monitors per census tract
  monitor_intract_count_no0 <- count(as_tibble(monitors_in_tract), GEOID)
  #find all other GEOIDs, count=0
  monitor_intract_count_only0 <- y[!(y$GEOID %in% monitor_intract_count_no0$GEOID),] %>% 
    as_tibble() %>% 
    select(GEOID)
  #one main dataframe for polygon of census tract and the number of monitors within it
  monitor_intract_count_only0$n <- 0
  monitor_intract_count_all <- rbind(monitor_intract_count_no0, monitor_intract_count_only0)
  
  #here is where z comes in
  #disadvantaged
  monitor_intract_count_dsad <- monitor_intract_count_all[(monitor_intract_count_all$GEOID %in% z$GEOID),]
  monitor_intract_count_dsad_vector <- monitor_intract_count_dsad$n
  #not disadvantaged
  monitor_intract_count_ad <- monitor_intract_count_all[!(monitor_intract_count_all$GEOID %in% z$GEOID),]
  monitor_intract_count_ad_vector <- monitor_intract_count_ad$n
  #independent 2-group t-test
  return(t.test(monitor_intract_count_dsad_vector, monitor_intract_count_ad_vector, var.equal = TRUE))
}

dist_ttest <- function(y, a, indicator) {
  z <- stjoin_filter(y, a, {{indicator}})
  min_dist_calculated <- select(y, min_dist_pa_aqs, GEOID)
  #disadvantaged
  min_dist_dsad <- min_dist_calculated[(min_dist_calculated$GEOID %in% z$GEOID),]
  min_dist_dsad_vector <- min_dist_dsad$min_dist_pa_aqs
  #not disadvantaged
  min_dist_ad <- min_dist_calculated[!(min_dist_calculated$GEOID %in% z$GEOID),]
  min_dist_ad_vector <- min_dist_ad$min_dist_pa_aqs
  #independent 2-group t-test
  return(t.test(min_dist_dsad_vector, min_dist_ad_vector, var.equal = TRUE))
}

o3_pm_ttest <- function(y, a, indicator, p) {
  z <- stjoin_filter(y, a, {{indicator}})
  tract_pop_CES4 <- st_join(y, a)
  o3_pm_all <- select(tract_pop_CES4, {{p}}, GEOID)
  #disadvantaged
  o3_pm_dsad <- o3_pm_all[(o3_pm_all$GEOID %in% z$GEOID),]
  o3_pm_dsad_vector <- pull(o3_pm_dsad, {{p}}) #new vector pulling format instead of df$col
  #not disadvantaged
  o3_pm_ad <- o3_pm_all[!(o3_pm_all$GEOID %in% z$GEOID),]
  o3_pm_ad_vector <- pull(o3_pm_ad, {{p}})
  #independent 2-group t-test
  return(t.test(o3_pm_dsad_vector, o3_pm_ad_vector, var.equal = TRUE))
}

asthma_stat <- read_csv("data_raw/Asthma_Stats_Visualizations.xlsx - Stats.csv") %>% 
  select(-N)
genhos_vs_pm25 <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average Hospitalizations (0-17)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
genhos_vs_pm25$indicator <- "Average Hospitalizations (0-17)"
genhos_vs_pm25$p <- "Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)"
genhos_vs_ozone <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average Hospitalizations (0-17)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average O3 (PPM)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
genhos_vs_ozone$indicator <- "Average Hospitalizations (0-17)"
genhos_vs_ozone$p <- "Average O3 (ppm)"
visit_vs_pm25 <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average ED Visits (0-17)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
visit_vs_pm25$indicator <- "Average ED Visits (0-17)"
visit_vs_pm25$p <- "Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)"
visit_vs_ozone <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average ED Visits (0-17)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average O3 (PPM)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
visit_vs_ozone$indicator <- "Average ED Visits (0-17)"
visit_vs_ozone$p <- "Average O3 (ppm)"

hos04_vs_pm25 <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average Hospitalizatons (0-4)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
hos04_vs_pm25$indicator <- "Average Hospitalizatons (0-4)"
hos04_vs_pm25$p <- "Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)"
hos04_vs_ozone <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average Hospitalizatons (0-4)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average O3 (PPM)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
hos04_vs_ozone$indicator <- "Average Hospitalizatons (0-4)"
hos04_vs_ozone$p <- "Average O3 (ppm)"
hos517_vs_pm25 <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average Hospitalizatons (5 to 17)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
hos517_vs_pm25$indicator <- "Average Hospitalizatons (5 to 17)"
hos517_vs_pm25$p <- "Average PM2.5 (ug/m3)"
hos517_vs_ozone <- t.test(asthma_stat$`Average Hospitalizatons (5 to 17)`, 
       asthma_stat$`Average O3 (PPM)`, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
hos517_vs_ozone$indicator <- "Average Hospitalizatons (5 to 17)"
hos517_vs_ozone$p <- "Average O3 (ppm)"
ashley_stuff <- rbind(genhos_vs_pm25, genhos_vs_ozone, visit_vs_ozone, visit_vs_pm25, 
                      hos04_vs_ozone, hos04_vs_pm25, hos517_vs_ozone, hos517_vs_pm25)

flex_ashley_stuff <- ashley_stuff %>% 
  select(indicator, p, statistic, p.value, parameter) %>% 
  rename(c(parameter = p, `t value` = statistic, `p value` = p.value, df = parameter)) %>% 
  flextable() %>% 
  theme_booktabs(bold_header=TRUE) %>% 
  add_footer_lines("Table 5: ") %>% 
  color(part = "footer", color = "#666666") %>% 
  autofit(add_w = 0, add_h = 0)
